To amend the European Stability Pact
The European Stability Pact, which supports the euro by setting constraints determining the size of budget deficits of Union members, is in danger.
Germany, the heavyweight of the Union, has not succeeded in meeting its budgetary commitments to its European partners.
Moreover, she used her political weight to cover the pre-warning of her deficit, which was set up by the European Commission according to the terms of the Stability Pact.
Today it's France that's playing the bad boy.
The number two at the Union, somewhat unenthusiastic, has in turn unofficially declared that he cannot honor his commitment to reduce the budget deficit, one year after small Ireland received an official warning regarding its fiscal policies, despite its budget surpluses, and in a very severe manner.
Thus, four years after its signing, the stability pact is a genuine disaster.
In fact, Europe appears to be significantly affected by the discussions aimed at eliminating it, as well as those aimed at amending it.
And rightfully so: the pact is poorly designed and its implementation is flawed.
The limitation of the deficit to 3% of GDP is arbitrary and ignores the fact that deficits automatically increase when the economy slows down.
By acknowledging this fact, the architects of the pact have worsened the situation by adopting two "poorly thought-out" solutions.
They introduced a safeguard clause allowing any country to suspend its deficit limits in case of significant recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is virtually impossible in practice.
Concerned that serious slowdowns could breach the deficit ceiling, they decreed that a normal deficit equaled a zero deficit.
Thus, every year, each country must submit a projection budget for the two years ahead demonstrating how budgetary balance will be achieved at that time.
The German commitment for 2002 was made in 2001, when its economy was developing at a reasonable pace.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from achieving its goals.
The translation of the given French sentence to English is:  "The finance minister, Hans Eichel, reasonably decided not to worsen the situation by adopting a fiscal policy of budgetary contraction."
The Commission, seeking to position itself as the protector of the pact, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be made by realpolitik politicians, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany, since everyone recognized that they could be confronted with the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was issued.
The situation of France is different.
During election periods, politicians inevitably make promises, particularly regarding tax relief.
In a country where tax burden is significant, it's not only about demonstrating political acumen, but also about showing economic acumen, as long as budget expenditures are minimized.
However, in France, everyone also enjoys certain privileges financed by the state, and as a result, budget cuts are definitively poorly perceived.
Thus, France cannot meet its targets, and the Commission has expressed its frustration.
But France has become skilled in defying the Union's laws.
Political maneuvers will inevitably follow.
Economists and cynics are not particularly surprised.
The objective of the pact, to establish a fiscal discipline among countries sharing the same currency, is entirely reasonable.
However, the loss of control over their national monetary policy means that members of the Union no longer benefit from more than one macroeconomic tool: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Just like promising to get on a diet before a big party, this challenge is not easy to balance.
The stability pact is too rudimentary and technocratic: the 3% target set by Brussels bureaucrats cannot bind the politicians in office.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Fortunately, we don't have to look far.
The monetary policy finds itself facing the same challenge.
She must stabilize long-term prices while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
In the last ten years, monetary policy enjoyed a real success.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it simply requires delegating this policy to a competent group, the central bank, and granting it the necessary political independence, as well as a clear and well-defined mandate.
Knowing that any mistake will have to be resolved in the future, it's up to him to show some common sense.
This has turned out to be one of the major improvements in the monetary field in recent years.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Of course, some fear losing in terms of democracy.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy fulfills two very different purposes.
The first one is structural and redistributive and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure both in terms of expenditures and revenues.
The decisions concerning these questions cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments and be subject to parliamentary approval and management.
The second is macroeconomic: it involves defining the budgetary balance to manage fluctuations in economic cycles.
It differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent agency.
Thus, the task of Europe is clear.
Here is the English translation of the given French sentence:  "Each country must regain full control of its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, decisions on deficits or surpluses, to an independent Fiscal Policy Committee whose long-term objective is the stabilization (or reduction, for some countries) of public debt."
To ensure the outcome, the status of such a Committee and its mandates must achieve a consensus within the Union, without any interference from Brussels, without any arbitrary regulation, without any political decision-making, but simply by relying on common sense.
